import fire
import subprocess

@fire.decorators.SetParseFn(str)
@fire.decorators.SetParseFns(number_of_repeats=int)
def repeat_command(number_of_repeats, *command):
  for _ in range(number_of_repeats):
    subprocess.call(command)

if __name__ == '__main__':
  fire.Fire(repeat_command)
```

This enables running a command multiple times like so:

> example.py 4 'echo hello world'

@gromgull 

see [my comment](https://github.com/RDFLib/rdflib/pull/504#issuecomment-126996238) on whether to use ``graphs()`` or not.

As for duplication or not: as [I said](https://github.com/RDFLib/rdflib/issues/495#issuecomment-126903646), just saying

```
def graphs(self,t):
    return self.contexts(t)
```

does not work because ``contexts`` is an iterator. I was not sure what the best way is to do that, maybe

```
def graphs(self,t):
    for s in self.contexts(s) : yield s
```

would work, but I did not have the time to test that (thinking about it further this should probably work!). There is probably a standard python idiom for this, but I do not know from the top of my head.

You can access the available features of a Neuron via three ways. You can load a neuron:
```python
from neurom.ezy import load_neuron
n = load_neuron('path_to_neuron')
```
And then write a dot after n and tab completion to find all the possible functions on the object.

You can load the ezyNeuron object
```python
from neurom.ezy import Neuron
```
and then do Neuron. and tab completion to see the available functions.

Or finally you can check the code for ezy.Neuron where will you find all the available functions. In the following block you can see the available features in NeuroM for a neuron object:
```
get_section_path_distances
get_section_radial_distances
get_local_bifurcation_angles
get_segment_lengths
get_soma_radius
get_n_sections
get_soma_surface_area
get_n_sections_per_neurite
get_trunk_origin_radii
get_remote_bifurcation_angles
get_trunk_section_lengths
get_section_lengths
```

Can you please provide us with information concerning features that are important/standard for classification and that which they aren't currently implemented in NeuroM. This is a useful test case in order to expand NeuroM's features.

As far as the features extraction is concerned, there is the morph_stats application in the app folder in NeuroM which takes a directory as an input, loads the neurons, extracts basic stats (e.g. mean, median, std etc.) for all the available features and stores them in a json file. The features value extraction is applied on all the vailable neurite types (e.g. axon, basals, all together, etc.).

