@rohitgcs thanks for raising the issue. You are not the first person to have this [request](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/issues/480).

I'd like to avoid implementing any timers in the logic here.
What you can do is in your application is you can wrap your incoming stream in a while loop which controls the timeout. Please see the example provided [here](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/issues/480#issuecomment-263854897)

@troydai @xingwu1 have addressed the major concerns and passing CI.  

With regards to nested try-excepts I will differ to judgement of what cli team wants in their codebase.

The main feasible alternate implementation I can think of involves returning from the try block and swallowing parsing errors. We still have the same amount of try blocks using this method but then they are sequential rather than embedded.

@asvetlov 
Fake Facebook server you can setup with `aiohttp.web.Application` - just implement endpoints you interested in, simulate original server behavior and run in background. But unlikely you would need in it - too much to code when result is still unknown. 

You can just simply mock all requests responses, defining what more-or-less Facebook will return to you and how your client would react on that. Same result, but less to code and no network round trips (faster tests in other words). Moreother, this way will allow you to make tests against exact real Facebook responces and track down regressions. With fake server I'm not sure how you'll do the same.

