The indexes are reported in the error output. A simple example:

```python
from marshmallow import Schema, fields


class Inner(Schema):
    foo = fields.Str(required=True)

class Outer(Schema):
    inners = fields.Nested(Inner, many=True)


in_data = {
    'inners': [{'foo': 'valid'}, {}]
}

schema = Outer()
print(schema.load(in_data).errors)
# {'inners': {1: {'foo': ['Missing data for required field.']}}}
```

Validators don't have access to indexes, however, so you'll likely have to postprocess the error output if you want to more complex things.

We don't plan on adding API to support indices in error messages, so I'm closing this for now. Feel free to reopen this if you have suggestions though.

@jeremy-murphy Thanks for reporting. We current test in CI GCC 4.8.2 however we don't test (and I have never tested) with a distro as old as CentOS 6.8.

IIUC the reason you see this error is that you're using a very old version of glibc. According to the `clock_gettime` man page it was only necessary to link with `librt` for glibc versions before 2.17.

The other build system explicitly passes `-lrt` to the compiler. We need to fix the CMake build system to link against this library when necessary.

This is my workaound attempt at fixing this issue. For M2M, I sent in the row parameter and use that to detect whether the value of the export is different than the value in the row. Note that this only works if the export value is unique. You'll have to modify the skip_row function to include the new row parameter.

    def skip_row_fix(self, instance, original, row):
        if not self._meta.skip_unchanged:
            return False
        for field in self.get_import_fields():
            if isinstance(field.widget, ManyToManyWidget):
                if self.export_field(field, original) != row[field.attribute]:
                    return False
            else:
                try:
                    if list(field.get_value(instance).all()) != list(field.get_value(original).all()):
                        return False
                except AttributeError:
                    if field.get_value(instance) != field.get_value(original):
                        return False
        return True

